results.notes:
Growing from large diameter fallen tree, possibly Inga sp, near a creek. The tree apparently fell several seasons ago, and is colonized by Rigidoporus, Earliella scabrosa, Phellinus, and other fleshy fungi. A large quantity was harvested, cooked, and shared among at least six individuals, including myself. The resulting texture and flavor to me is comparable or tastier than cultivated Pleurotus, and better than wild P. djamor. Spores from this collection were used to cultivate observation 403850

results.notes:
Growing from dead, standing “yagrumo” (Schefflera or Cecropia). I initially thought these were Pleurotus “albidus” which I have collected here before, but the gills of P. albidus are very broad and P. albidus has a white, cottony patch at the disc. This taxon differs in having compressed stipes which are conspicuously fused and have a pink or lilac tint. Otherwise they have very different micromorphology. This taxon has unserrated lamellae which do not become subporoid and a tomentum on the stipe that is appreciable through a handlens. Hymenophoral trama is irregular. I am sure that observation 366407 also represents this taxon. Spores are almost subglobose, small, abundant, and observed developing on relatively long sterigmata. The morphology of the spores and the presence of elements like pleurocystidia (gloeocystidia?) in the trama would seem to eliminate Lentinus concavus as a possible ID.

results.notes:
On the Foothills area just above Boise. On sandy soil with sagebrush on grass. A few trees 200 feet away in people yards, nothing closer. Terrestrial. The caps are around 5 cms.
The cap is yellow/brown, peach color, to orange/brown, bald and moist. Maybe sub-viscid.
Gills are close, notched, adnate, broad.
The stipe is whitish, or light yellow/brown, hollow, tapering down. Strong mycelia not letting go of the debris.
The spore prints between cinnamon brown to dull brown, no traces of yellow, orange or rush brown.
I think I see some fibrils on the top of the stipe, without having a defined ring zone. No yellow veils.
Flesh taste and odor are mild.
Spores elliptical 6.3 – 6.7 X 4.3 – 4.7, smooth to maybe minutely rough.
Initially, my guess was towards Cortinarius subgenus Telamonia. Now, because it grows around sagebrush, and the color print is dull brown, and the spores been smooth, I don’t know.
